 and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":9,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert de Grenville was born about 1215, in Hallaton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Eustace de Grenville, was 32 and his mother, Joan Arsic, was 26. He married Joyouse Prested in 1238, in Colne Engaine, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 2 November 1243, in Hallaton, Leicestershire, England, at the age of 29, and was buried in Hallaton, Leicestershire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1215–2 November 1243":"umbes 1215–2. november 1243","1215–1243":"1215–1243","1220–1309":"1220–1309","1215–1274":"1215–1274","1236–1305":"1236–1305","1184–1241":"1184–1241","1190–1241":"1190–1241","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","Abt 1215":"umbes 1215","1241":"1241","1274":"1274","1184":"1184","after 2 November 1243":"pärast 2. novembrit 1243","1305":"1